    comment: '<h3>Mark Text</h3>\n<p>The <code>&#x3C;mark></code>, or the <strong>Mark Text</strong> element, is used to specify that some text is marked or highlighted. The <code>&#x3C;mark></code> element is often used to indicate a part of the text of the document that is relevant to the user\'s search.</p>\n<pre><code class="language-html">&#x3C;p>Highlight this\n&#x3C;mark>important&#x3C;/mark>\ntext in this paragraph.&#x3C;/p>\n</code></pre>\n<p><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="320" height="76"><g fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"><rect width="320" height="76" fill="#FFF" rx="9"/><path fill="#FFFF02" d="M117 21h71v17h-71z"/><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="16"><tspan x="20" y="34">Highlight this important text in </tspan> <tspan x="20" y="53">this paragraph.</tspan></text></g></svg></p>\n<!--[View CodePen](https://codepen.io/enkidevs/pen/GBrJdP)-->\n<p>The text within the <code>&#x3C;mark></code> element is usually rendered with a yellow background, but the <code>background-color: yellow;</code> of the element can be changed using CSS.</p>\n<p>Also, when <code>&#x3C;mark></code> is used within a <code>&#x3C;q></code> or <code>&#x3C;blockquote></code> element it indicates that that text is important even though it is not marked by the original author as important. This is like highlighting important text from a book with a marker/highlighter.</p>\n<h3>Unarticulated Annotation</h3>\n<p>The <code>&#x3C;u></code>, or the <strong>Unarticulated Annotation</strong> element, is used to indicate that some text should be rendered differently from the rest of the text in a way that indicated non-textual annotation. The content of the <code>&#x3C;u></code> element is usually rendered as underlined. Nevertheless, you can change this by using the appropriate CSS styling - from this <code>text-decoration: underline;</code> to something like <code>text-decoration: #f00 wavy underline;</code>.</p>\n<pre><code class="language-html">&#x3C;p>You could use this element\nto highlight &#x3C;u>speling&#x3C;/u>\nmistakes, so the writer\ncan &#x3C;u>corect&#x3C;/u> them.&#x3C;/p>\n</code></pre>\n<p><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="320" height="94"><g fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"><rect width="320" height="94" fill="#FFF" rx="9"/><path stroke="#FF1018" d="M94 76.5c-.23565 2.0467.59768 2.71337 2.5 2 2.85347-1.07005 2.37848-5 5-5s2.5 5 5 5 2.37152-5 5-5 2.37848 5 5 5 3.25284-5 5.5-5 2.5 5 5 5 2.81456-5 5.5-5 2.68544 4.62441 4 5c.87638.2504 1.87638-.7496 3-3M88 57.5c-.23565 2.0467.59768 2.71337 2.5 2 2.85347-1.07005 2.37848-5 5-5s3 5 5.5 5 2.37152-5 5-5 3.359 5 5.98052 5c2.62152 0 2.27232-5 4.51948-5 2.24716 0 3 5 5.5 5s2.81456-5 5.5-5 3.68544 4.62441 5 5c.87638.2504 2.2097-.91627 4-3.5"/><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto" font-size="16"><tspan x="20" y="34">You could use this element to </tspan> <tspan x="20" y="53">highlight speling mistakes, so the </tspan> <tspan x="20" y="72">writer can corect them.</tspan></text></g></svg></p>\n<!--[View CodePen](https://codepen.io/enkidevs/pen/OwWVBe)-->\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> The <code>&#x3C;u></code> element used to be called the <code>Underline</code> element before when it was only used to underline text. If you wish to set some text as underline, you should not use the <code>&#x3C;u></code> element to style it but rather the appropriate CSS properties.</p>\n<p>Also, when using the <code>&#x3C;u></code> element you should give it a different style than underlined because users may confuse them with hyperlinks.</p>\n<p>The <code>&#x3C;u></code> element is often used to annotate spelling errors, proper nouns and/or names in Chinese, and other annotations.</p>\n',
